            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">JEWS IN <hi rend="underline"
                ><placeName>TURKEY</placeName>.</hi></p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Smyrna</placeName>, <date>January 24, 1855</date>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>ISAAC LEESER, ESQ.</addressee>:—Dear Sir—<persName>Mr.
                    Mitchell</persName>, of your<lb/> city, <sic>s</sic> friend of yours, was
                several days detained in<lb/> this city, and fortunately I became acquainted
                with<lb/> him. He requested me to address a letter to you, giv-<lb/>ing you some
                information respecting the Jews in this<lb/> place and in this vicinity. This I
                readily assented<lb/> to do; but I <sic>mustconfess</sic> to negligence in allowing
                so<lb/> many weeks to pass without fulfilling my promise. I<lb/> shall not set it
                down entirely as negligence; for I<lb/> have been so fully occupied that I have not
                found time<lb/> to write many letters to personal relatives, which I<lb/>
                acknowledge as due from me. But as I have at present<lb/> no time to spare I will
                not prolong to apologize.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I came to this country in the year <date>1850</date>, as
                mission-<lb/>ary to the Jews of the A.B.C.F.M. Two years we were<lb/> in
                    <placeName>Thessalonica</placeName>, six months, on account of health, in<lb/>
                <placeName>Constantinople</placeName>, and the rest of the time in this city.<lb/>
                While in <placeName>Thessalonica</placeName> I made several short
                tours—ra-<lb/>ther, one long one and one short one. I will give you<lb/> the names
                of the Jewish places and their population,<lb/> as nearly as I can be tolerably
                certain of correctness.<lb/> You know how difficult it is to obtain exact
                statistics.</p>
            <p>—————————————————</p>
            <p>——————-</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr. Mitchell</persName> said he would send me a copy of
                your<lb/> paper, which I am sure will be very valuable to us,<lb/> in giving
                extracts from it, and information respecting<lb/> the Jews in
                    <placeName>America</placeName>. The very appearance of your<lb/> beautiful
                journal (of which <persName>Mr. M.</persName> showed me a copy)<lb/> would be a
                marvel to our Jewish friends here, when told<lb/> that it was published by a Jew. I
                told <persName>Mr. Mitchell</persName><lb/> that I should value very highly the back
                numbers of<lb/> your periodical; he said he would inquire if they could<lb/> be
                furnished, and at what price. I trust he will not<lb/> forget it, or that you will
                be so kind as to inform me<lb/> directly.</p>
            <p>If you have any particular inquiries to make, I shall</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p><del>?</del> be most happy to<lb/> answer them as far as I am able.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Your work is arduous, but I trust you will see the<lb/> benefit
                resulting to your people. May the Lord bless<lb/> you; and I remain yours,
                truly,</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">J. W. PARSONS</persName>.</p>
            <p>
                <hi rend="underline">Occ. Vol. XIII, <sic>page45</sic>; <date>Nissan 5615, April
                        1855</date>. </hi>
            </p>
